    Demo Task 06 - Complaint investigation (In Progress / Investigation)
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the SIXTH of the 8-task demo dataset; together with
    tasks 01 through 05 and tasks 07 and 08, it satisfies the AAP
    requirement (Section 0.7.4) of providing demo tasks that exercise
    the resolve-blocker and resolve-success gates on both case-type
    flows. The complete 8-task fixture matrix:

        Task 01 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Task 02 - Closed      / Investigation / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Task 03 - Open        / Follow-up     / parent case 04 (Pending GI)
        Task 04 - Closed      / Investigation / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Task 05 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Task 06 - In Progress / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)  ## THIS FILE
        Task 07 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Task 08 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 09 (Resolved Complaint)

    The 8-task dataset thus exercises:
      * All 4 task types - this task contributes one of four Investigation
        entries (the others are tasks 01, 04, and 07); the Investigation
        type semantically represents the agent's evidence-gathering and
        information-collection action on a case.
      * All 3 task statuses (Open, In Progress, Closed) - this task
        UNIQUELY contributes the SOLE In Progress task status entry in
        the entire 8-task dataset. None of the other seven demo tasks
        carries the middle-state In Progress status; tasks 01, 03, and
        07 are Open, and tasks 02, 04, 05, and 08 are Closed. Per AAP
        Section 0.5.7, the case_task status Choice list defines exactly
        three values - Open, In Progress, Closed - and this task is
        the canonical demonstrator that the middle status state is
        accepted by the table-level dictionary entry, surfaces correctly
        on the form, and is correctly counted as non-Closed by the
        validate_resolved_transition subflow's GlideRecord query.
      * 5 unique parent cases (03, 04, 05, 08, 09) - this task is the
        FIRST child of case 08 (the second being task 07); together,
        tasks 06 + 07 give case 08 TWO non-Closed child tasks
        (In Progress + Open), demonstrating that the resolve gate's
        GlideRecord query correctly counts ALL non-Closed children, not
        just the first one encountered.
      * Both flow paths (General Inquiry and Complaint) - tasks 06 + 07
        together test the COMPLAINT flow's resolve-BLOCKER path; tasks
        01 + 02 test the GENERAL INQUIRY flow's resolve-blocker path;
        tasks 04 + 05 test the GENERAL INQUIRY flow's resolve-success
        path; task 08 tests the COMPLAINT flow's resolve-success path.
      * Both resolve outcomes (BLOCKED via at least one non-Closed task,
        and SUCCESS via zero non-Closed tasks) - this task is the
        FIRST blocker on case 08 (paired with task 07), establishing
        that the resolve-blocker fires whenever the count of non-Closed
        children is >= 1, regardless of whether that count is 1 or many,
        and regardless of WHICH non-Closed status (Open or In Progress)
        each child carries.

    Lifecycle position - WHY In Progress / Investigation / parent
    Complaint case In Progress is meaningful:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.5 the resolve gate's GlideRecord query
      executed inside the validate_resolved_transition subflow is:

          var gr = new GlideRecord('x_[scope]_case_task');
          gr.addQuery('case', current.sys_id);
          gr.addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed');
          gr.query();
          if (gr.next()) {
              // BLOCK: surface the verbatim error message
              //   "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
          } else {
              // ALLOW: zero non-Closed tasks - case may be Resolved
          }

      Case 08 is in In Progress status with type=Complaint. With this
      In Progress child task PLUS task 07's Open status, the query
      "case = case 08 AND status != Closed" returns TWO rows. The
      subflow blocks any attempt to transition case 08 to Resolved and
      surfaces the verbatim error "All tasks must be closed before
      resolving this case." THIS TASK + TASK 07 ARE THE CANONICAL
      RESOLVE-BLOCKER PAIR FOR THE COMPLAINT FLOW. Where tasks 01 + 02
      perform this role for case 03 on the General Inquiry flow, this
      task with task 07 performs the same role for case 08 on the
      Complaint flow.

      The Investigation task type captures the agent's evidence-
      gathering action on the case. Per the AAP's Complaint case-
      handling pattern, an investigation is a typical mid-lifecycle
      step in the agent's workflow - the agent actively works through
      collecting facts, interviewing witnesses, reviewing records, and
      synthesizing findings BEFORE reaching a conclusion. The
      "Complaint investigation" subject makes this lifecycle phase
      explicit. The In Progress status is consistent with this active-
      work semantic: the agent has begun (so the task is past Open) but
      has not yet finished (so the task is not yet Closed).

      The +7 days due_date reflects the longer time-horizon of an
      active investigation - the broader investigation spans roughly a
      week, contrasting with task 07's near-term +3 days due_date for
      a specific prep step (witness interview prep). The relative date
      pattern uses positive offsets (in 7 days) for active/upcoming
      tasks, consistent with In Progress status semantics (a task that
      has been started, is currently being worked, and has a target
      completion date that is both in the future and not yet imminent).
      The +7 days value is also longer than task 03's +5 days (a
      Pending-case Follow-up) and task 01's +5 days (a General Inquiry
      Investigation), reinforcing that Critical-priority Complaint
      investigations are typically given a longer working window than
      lower-priority tasks of the same type.

